initial_story:
The Eurovision Song Contest is just around the corner and this year, it's taking place in Malmo, Sweden.

You can find out all about the event right here.

The UK's entry for 2024 is Olly Alexander who'll be performing his song, Dizzy.

But how's he feeling ahead of the big night, where he'll perform in front of 200 million people!

De-Graft sat down with him to find out all about his preparation for the competition.

The Eurovision Song contest Grand Final will be shown on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May.
stories: "I've been preparing for this moment for a while now," Olly tells me, his voice filled with a mix of excitement and nerves. "I've been working closely with my team to perfect my performance, and I've also been doing a lot of vocal exercises to make sure my voice is in top condition."

"I have to say, I'm feeling a bit like a pressure cooker waiting to burst, just thinking about going on stage," Olly confesses, his eyes scanning the room as if searching for an escape route. "But at the same time, I'm so ready to finally share my music with the world and show everyone what I'm capable of."

"What's making it hard is that I've put so much pressure on myself to make this perfect, to not disappoint the fans and my team, but at the same time, I don't want to put too much pressure on myself and end up bottling it all up like I have been for so long."

"I'm trying to find that balance between pushing myself to be great and not letting the weight of expectation crush me. It's exhausting, to be honest. I just wish I could show up to the game without all this mental clutter and just play ball."

"I know I'm not alone in this feeling, but it's hard to believe that right now. Every little thing feels magnified, like the crowd is chanting my name and I'm expected to perform at an Olympic level. I just want to breathe, you know? I want to let go of the need for perfection and just be in the moment. But how do I silence the voices in my head telling me I'm not good enough?"

"It's like I'm trapped in a never-ending loop of self-doubt, where every negative thought is amplified a thousand times. I feel like I'm constantly playing catch-up, trying to prove myself to everyone else. But the truth is, I'm already exhausted from trying to live up to everyone's expectations. I'm trying to tune in to the voices telling me I'm good enough, but they're drowned out by the noise of my own self-criticism. Maybe I just need to take a step back, focus on my own needs, and remind myself that I'm more than just my limitations. But how do I silence the whispers that I'm not good enough when it feels like the entire world is screaming it in my ear?"

"I'm starting to realize that maybe I'm not the problem, maybe I'm just a reflection of all the societal pressures and expectations that I've been conditioned to believe. But if that's the case, then why do I feel so lost and unsure? Why do I doubt my own abilities and worthiness? I need to learn to break free from this cycle of self-doubt and start embracing my imperfections. I need to remind myself that nobody is perfect, that we're all works in progress. I need to focus on my strengths, not my weaknesses. And most of all, I need to learn to be kind to myself and treat myself with the same compassion and understanding that I would give to a friend."

"This means letting go of the relentless pursuit of perfection, accepting that it's okay to make mistakes and that they are an inevitable part of growth. It means taking small steps towards self-acceptance, rather than striving for some idealized version of myself that exists only in my mind. It means speaking kindly to myself when I make a mistake, rather than beating myself up over it. It means reminding myself that I am doing the best I can, and that that's enough. And it means embracing my authenticity, quirks and all, rather than trying to fit into some mold or conform to societal expectations. The journey ahead won't be easy, but I'm ready to take the first step and start embracing my true self."

"As I take this first step, I begin to realize that the weight I've been carrying around is slowly lifting. I feel a sense of freedom in acknowledging that I don't have to be perfect, and that it's okay to not have all the answers. I start to see myself not as a work in progress, but as a beautifully flawed work of art, with strokes of beauty and imperfection blended together. I begin to whisper affirmations to myself, reminding me of my worth and reminding myself that I am enough, just as I am. The more I accept myself, the more I start to see the world with fresh eyes, free from the burden of expectation. It's a gentle, quiet revolution, one that starts within and radiates outward. I am learning to love myself, just as I am, and that's the greatest gift of all."

"As I continue on this journey, I find myself letting go of the need for validation from others, and instead focusing on cultivating a deep sense of self-love and self-acceptance.
